    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Test samples' factor in ASME V&V 40 addresses physical test article characterization — specifically the representativeness of manufactured test specimens with respect to production devices (e.g., dimensional tolerances, material lot variability). This COU uses the FDA generic centrifugal pump, which is a standardized reference geometry defined by a published CAD file (FDA 2017) rather than manufactured physical specimens with inter-unit variability. All experimental data were collected on a single reference impeller fabricated to tight tolerance from the FDA CAD file; there is no population of test samples with manufacturing variation to characterize. Accordingly, the factor does not apply to this assessment and is scoped out with this documented rationale."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor addresses situations where physical test inputs must be mapped to simulation inputs through a non-trivial equivalency argument — typically arising when the validation experiment uses a scaled or surrogate fluid whose properties differ substantially from the COU fluid, requiring dimensionless parameter matching (e.g., Reynolds number, Stokes number equivalency). In this assessment, the validation experiments use porcine blood at physiological hematocrit (35%) and temperature (37°C), which directly matches the COU fluid properties; the CFD model uses the same fluid property values measured from the test fluid. There is no scaling or surrogate fluid involved, and the input parameters are applied directly without equivalency transformation. The factor therefore does not apply."
    }
